column18:
STUDY DESCRIPTION AND CONSENT

 

We are asking you to take part in a research study being done by Dr. John Hunter at Chapman University. Being in this study is optional, but if you choose to be in the study, you will be asked you to respond to a variety of questions related to your well-being, your perception of yourself and others, your thoughts, and your emotions. You may also be asked to engage in activities that support your well-being. This will help us learn more about student well-being throughout a semester. 

NOTE: PLEASE DO NOT PROCEED IF YOU ARE UNDER THE AGE OF 18.

 

TIME INVOLVEMENT: The study will require you to fill out 4 short surveys over a 6-week period. First, you will fill out a baseline survey (~15 minutes). After two weeks, you will be asked to fill out another brief survey (~5 minutes). After four weeks, you will be asked to fill out another brief survey (~5 minutes). At the conclusion of the study, you will fill out a follow-up survey (~15 minutes).

   


RISKS AND BENEFITS: Some questions will ask you about your general mental health and well-being, which could cause some discomfort. You can exit the survey at any time. Your answers have nothing to do with your grade, and you will not be graded on your performance. A potential benefit is the opportunity to check in with your personal well-being and explore how completing Flourish activities can enhance your life and connections. After all, your mental health is just as important as (if not more important than) your academics. In addition, you will be contributing to broader public health research to better understand the experiences of students like you.



COMPENSATION: Upon completion of all four surveys, you will be compensated with one SONA credit. 



PRIVACY AND CONFIDENTIALITY: Participant identities will remain completely confidential in this study. We will not release your responses in any way that could identify you. Data will be compiled and summarized for academic publications, research briefs, or presentations in a way that does not allow your responses to be identifiable. The anonymized data will be deposited on the Open Science Framework repository and will be made available to the public who wish to re-analyze the data based on open science. As in any data collection, there is risk of breach of confidentiality, but we make every effort to keep your study data confidential and not share your personal information with anyone outside the research team.



CONTACT INFORMATION:

Questions: If you have questions about this research, you may contact the study’s Principal Investigator, Dr. John Hunter, at johnhunter@chapman.edu If you have questions or concerns about your rights as a research participant, you may contact the Chapman University Institutional Review Board at irb@chapman.edu or (714) 628-2833.

column122: A more structured view of my mental health (like if the app focused on tracking mental health and mood and potential coping skills a person used in the moment) and what progress I am making and where I can improve. Sometimes it can be hard to see the progress day-by-day, but there are drastic changes being made. I think it would be beneficial to me if I was able to track my mental health and how I act on certain behaviors depending on internal and external factors. I honestly do not know why I have not really thought about downloading an app, but now I will probably look up an app as soon as I am done with this survey!
column123: I do not like the idea of apps where people can communicate with each other. For a little, I thought about downloading a couple apps that track a person's negative coping skills and show how long a person has been clean for. My younger sister used this and said that when she was doing really well, it was so cool to see all the positive comments, but if she relapsed, the people starting on day 1 a lot of the time were writing awful things about themselves. I think this would make me incredibly sad and lead to more negative behaviors, at least for me. Plus, although I am sure not all comments are negative for day 1 of the app, I also feel like it continues my thought process of relapsing as a sign of failure and a restart despite it merely being a misstep in my journey.
